What are streams in Node.js?
In Node.js, streams are a way to handle data piece by piece (chunks) instead of loading everything into memory at once.

Think of it like watching a video on YouTube — you don’t download the full video first; it loads continuously. That’s exactly how streams work.

🔹 Why Streams?
Without streams:

File is loaded completely into memory ❌

Slow + memory heavy ❌

With streams:

Data is processed in chunks ✅

Faster + memory efficient ✅

🔹 Types of Streams in Node.js

1. Readable Stream (Read data)
   Used to read data from a source

const fs = require('fs');

const readable = fs.createReadStream('file.txt');

readable.on('data', chunk => {
console.log(chunk.toString());
}); 2. Writable Stream (Write data)
Used to write data to a destination

const fs = require('fs');

const writable = fs.createWriteStream('output.txt');

writable.write('Hello World');
writable.end(); 3. Duplex Stream (Read + Write)
Can do both simultaneously

Example:

TCP sockets

4. Transform Stream (Modify data)
   A special duplex stream that transforms data

Example:

Compression, encryption

const zlib = require('zlib');

const gzip = zlib.createGzip();
🔹 Pipe Method (Most Important 🚀)
Streams can be connected using .pipe()

const fs = require('fs');

fs.createReadStream('input.txt')
.pipe(fs.createWriteStream('output.txt'));
👉 This reads and writes chunk by chunk automatically

🔹 Real-Life Examples
File upload/download

Video streaming (like Netflix/Hotstar)

API data handling

Large log processing

🔹 Key Advantages
Memory efficient

Faster processing

Handles large data easily

Supports backpressure (prevents overload)

